05031nam a22005895i 9780226553405DE-B159720191022022751.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191022s2018    ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802265534057 a10.7208/97802265534052doi  a(DE-B1597)524658  a(OCoLC)1065537491  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aGA5 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a523.1089927622231 aRapoport, Yossef, eauthor.10aLost Maps of the Caliphs :bDrawing the World in Eleventh-Century Cairo /cEmilie Savage-Smith, Yossef Rapoport. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (368 p.) :b25 color plates, 89 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tChapter One. A Discovery -- tChapter Two. Macrocosm to Microcosm: Reading the Skies and Stars in Fatimid Egypt -- tChapter Three. The Rectangular World Map -- tChapter Four. The Nile, the Mountain of the Moon, and the White Sand Dunes -- tChapter Five. The View from the Sea: Navigation and Representation of Maritime Space -- tChapter Six. Ports, Gates, Palaces: Drawing Fatimid Power on the Island-City Maps -- tChapter Seven. The Fatimid Mediterranean -- tChapter Eight. A Musk Road to China -- tChapter Nine. Down the African Coast, from Aden to the Island of the Crocodile -- tChapter Ten. The Book of Curiosities and the Islamic Geographical Tradition -- tConclusion. Maps, Seas, and the Ismaʿili Mission -- tAppendix. A Technical Discourse on Star Lore and Astrology -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAbout a millennium ago, in Cairo, an unknown author completed a large and richly illustrated book. In the course of thirty-five chapters, this book guided the reader on a journey from the outermost cosmos and planets to Earth and its lands, islands, features, and inhabitants. This treatise, known as The Book of Curiosities, was unknown to modern scholars until a remarkable manuscript copy surfaced in 2000. Lost Maps of the Caliphs provides the first general overview of The Book of Curiosities and the unique insight it offers into medieval Islamic thought. Opening with an account of the remarkable discovery of the manuscript and its purchase by the Bodleian Library, the authors use The Book of Curiosities to re-evaluate the development of astrology, geography, and cartography in the first four centuries of Islam. Their account assesses the transmission of Late Antique geography to the Islamic world, unearths the logic behind abstract maritime diagrams, and considers the palaces and walls that dominate medieval Islamic plans of towns and ports. Early astronomical maps and drawings demonstrate the medieval understanding of the structure of the cosmos and illustrate the pervasive assumption that almost any visible celestial event had an effect upon life on Earth. Lost Maps of the Caliphs also reconsiders the history of global communication networks at the turn of the previous millennium. It shows the Fatimid Empire, and its capital Cairo, as a global maritime power, with tentacles spanning from the eastern Mediterranean to the Indus Valley and the East African coast. As Lost Maps of the Caliphs makes clear, not only is The Book of Curiosities one of the greatest achievements of medieval mapmaking, it is also a remarkable contribution to the story of Islamic civilization that opens an unexpected window to the medieval Islamic view of the world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aAstronomy, MedievalzEgyptzCairo. 0aCartographyvEarly works to 1800. 0aCartographyzEgyptzCairoxHistoryyTo 1500. 0aCosmographyvEarly works to 1800. 0aGeographyvEarly works to 1800. 4aastrology. 4acartography. 4amaritime charts. 4aportolans. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh1 aSavage-Smith, Emilie, eauthor.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226553405423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226553405.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles